.TH DISKDIAG 8 "2026" "diskdiag" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
diskdiag \- sequential read latency test with ASCII heatmap
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B diskdiag
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.I device
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B diskdiag
performs a sequential read of a block device, measures the latency of
each block and renders an ASCII heatmap of results. Unlike SMART attribute
readers, it exercises the actual read path and reports real-world latency
distribution, making it useful for detecting degraded areas, ageing HDD
heads, or failing flash cells.
.PP
The device is opened with
.B O_DIRECT
to bypass the page cache, so results reflect physical media performance.
.PP
If the device is currently mounted,
.B diskdiag
prints a warning to stderr and asks for confirmation.
Use
.B \-y
to suppress the prompt in scripts.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-b " MiB" ", \-\-block\-size=" MiB
Read block size in mebibytes. Must be between 1 and 1024. Default: 1.
.TP
.BI \-n " N" ", \-\-blocks=" N
Read only the first
.I N
blocks instead of the whole device. Useful for a quick smoke test.
.TP
.BI \-o " N" ", \-\-offset=" N
Start reading at block offset
.IR N .
Can be combined with
.B \-n
to test a specific region of the disk.
.TP
.BI \-\-threshold\-warn= ms
Latency above which a block is counted as slow. Default: 20 ms.
.TP
.BI \-\-threshold\-error= ms
Latency above which a block is counted as an error. Default: 150 ms.
Must be greater than
.BR \-\-threshold\-warn .
.TP
.BR \-y ", " \-\-yes
Skip the interactive prompt when the device is mounted. The warning
is still printed to stderr. Intended for scripted or automated use.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress the progress bar and heatmap. Only the statistics table is
printed. Useful when redirecting output to a log file.
.TP
.BR \-j ", " \-\-json
Print results as a JSON object to stdout. The progress bar and heatmap
are suppressed. Mount warnings still go to stderr. Suitable for
machine-readable pipelines.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-color
Disable ANSI colour escape codes. Automatically enabled when stdout
is not a terminal (pipe, redirect).
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print usage information and exit.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0  HEALTHY
Fewer than 1\~% slow blocks and no read errors.
.TP
.B 1  GOOD
Between 1\~% and 5\~% slow blocks.
.TP
.B 2  FAIR
More than 5\~% slow blocks.
.TP
.B 3  POOR
Read errors detected, or block latency \(>= error threshold.
.TP
.B 4
Runtime error: bad arguments, device cannot be opened, etc.
.SH HEATMAP
Each cell in the heatmap represents the average latency of one region.
Characters and colours encode the latency bucket relative to the
configured thresholds:
.RS
.TP
.BR '.' "  (green)"
Very fast (< warn/4)
.TP
.BR 'o' "  (green)"
Fast (< warn/2)
.TP
.BR '*' "  (green)"
Normal (< warn)
.TP
.BR '#' "  (yellow)"
Slow (< error/3)
.TP
.BR 'X' "  (red)"
Very slow (< error)
.TP
.BR '!' "  (magenta)"
Critical (\(>= error threshold)
.TP
.BR 'E' "  (magenta)"
Read error returned by the kernel
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
Full test of a secondary drive:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo diskdiag /dev/sdb
.RE
.PP
Quick smoke test of the first 1000 blocks with 4 MiB blocks:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo diskdiag \-b 4 \-n 1000 /dev/sdb
.RE
.PP
Test a specific region (blocks 500\(en999):
.PP
.RS
.B sudo diskdiag \-o 500 \-n 500 /dev/sdb
.RE
.PP
Non-interactive JSON output for use in a monitoring script:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo diskdiag \-y \-q \-\-json /dev/sdb > result.json
.RE
.PP
Check exit code in a shell script:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sudo diskdiag \-y \-q /dev/sdb
case $? in
  0) echo "Healthy" ;;
  1) echo "Good" ;;
  2) echo "Fair \- investigation recommended" ;;
  3) echo "POOR \- immediate attention required" ;;
esac
.fi
.RE
.PP
Tighter thresholds for NVMe drives:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo diskdiag \-\-threshold\-warn 2 \-\-threshold\-error 20 /dev/nvme0n1
.RE
.SH NOTES
.B diskdiag
requires read access to the raw block device, which typically means
running as root.
.PP
For the most accurate results, test an unmounted disk or boot from a
live USB. Results on a mounted, active system may show elevated latency
due to competing I/O from the kernel.
.PP
.B Typical latency reference values:
.RS
.TP
NVMe SSD
< 1 ms
.TP
SATA SSD
1\(en5 ms
.TP
HDD (healthy)
5\(en20 ms
.TP
HDD (degraded)
> 50 ms
.RE
.PP
Sustained latency above 50 ms on a spinning disk is a strong indicator of
head issues or imminent failure.
.SH BUILD
.nf
gcc \-O2 \-Wall \-o diskdiag diskdiag.c \-lm
make && sudo make install
.fi
